Question 1

You didn't Attempt

Your time taken: 5s
Theory of Computation

Consider the following options and select the correct one.[MSQ]

Every language has a superset which is regular.

Correct answer

Every language has a subset which is regular.

Correct answer

Every subset of regular language must be regular.

Every superset of regular language must be regular.

Solution

Hide

Every language has a superset ∑* and every language has a subset ∅ {empty language}. 

Every subset of a regular language need not be regular. For ex: L={ a^n b^n | n>0} (non-regular) is subset of a*b*. 

Every superset of a regular language need not be regular. For ex: L={ a^n b^n | n>0} (non-regular) is a superset of L2={ab, aabb, aaabbb}. L2 is a finite language hence regular and L is a superset of L2 which is non regular.

Question 2

You didn't Attempt

Your time taken: 0s
Types of Languages

Consider the following options and select the correct one.[MSQ]

Union of two non-regular languages can never be regular.

Union of two regular languages can never be non-regular.

Correct answer

Union of a regular language with a non regular language can be regular also.

Correct answer

If (L1 U L2) is regular then L1 and L2 both must be regular.

Solution

Hide

Union of two regular languages must always be regular, since regular languages are closed under union.


Union of two non-regular languages can be regular also. For example, assume a DCFL (non-regular) and its complement. Both are non-regular. But their union will be ∑* which is regular.  


Union of a regular language with a non regular language can be regular also and if (L1 U L2) is regular then L1 and L2 need not be regular.


 For example:

L1=a*b* and L2={ a^n b^n | n>0}

L1 U L2 = L1 [Since L1 is superset of L2]

Theory of Computation

Assume L1=a*b* and L2=b*a* then (L1 ∩ L2) will be____

{∈}

∅

a*+b*

Correct answer

a*b*a*

Solution

Hide

L1 will contain strings {∈, a, aa, aaa, …., b, bb,bbb, ...ab, aab, abb, aabb, …….}

L2 will contain strings {∈, a, aa, aaa, …., b, bb,bbb, ...ba, bba, baa, bbaa, …….}


The common strings in L1 and L2 are {∈, a, aa, aaa, …., b, bb,bbb,.........}

Hence L1 ∩ L2= a*+b*

Question 11

You didn't Attempt

Your time taken: 0s
Turing Machine Construction

Let Np and Nt denote the class of languages recognized by non-deterministic push down automata and non-deterministic Turing machine respectively. Let Dp and Dt denote the class of languages recognized by deterministic push down automata and deterministic Turing machine respectively. Which one of the following is true? [MSQ]

Np ⊂ Nt and Dp ⊂ Dt

Correct answer

Dp ⊂ Np and Dt = Nt

Correct answer

Dp ⊂ Np and Dt ⊂ Nt

Dp ⊂ Nt and Np ⊂ Dt

Correct answer

Solution

Hide

The class of languages accepted by deterministic PDA is a proper subset of the class of languages accepted by non-deterministic PDA, while the class of languages accepted by deterministic TM is equivalent to the class of languages accepted by non-deterministic TM.

Hence Dt ⊂ Nt is false.

Also the class of languages accepted by non-deterministic PDA is a proper subset of the class of languages accepted by TM hence Np ⊂ Nt, Dp ⊂ Dt, Dp ⊂ Nt and Np ⊂ Dt are true.

Question 13

You didn't Attempt

Your time taken: 0s
Types of Languages

Consider the language L= {01, 101, 011, 00}, which of the following strings will be present in L*. [MSQ]

ϵ

Correct answer

0110100000101

Correct answer

1011010110001011

Correct answer

0001101011011100

Solution

Hide

L* will contain all those strings which can be obtained by any combination (and repetition) of the strings in language i,e, from L= { 01, 101, 011, 00 }. Also note that L* will always contain epsilon (null string)

String: 0110100000101 = 01 101 00 00 01 01, hence it is in L*.

String: 1011010110001011 = 101 101 011 00 01 011, hence it is in L*.

String: 0001101011011100 = 00 01 101 011 011 1 00 because of this extra “1” the string is not in L*.


Question 14

You didn't Attempt

Your time taken: 0s
Comparison of DFA and NFA

Consider the following statements and select the correct one.

For any state q, the epsilon closure of q may be an empty set, i.e. epsilon closure (q) = 𝜙

For any state q, the epsilon closure of q may be set of all states Q present in NFA, i.e. epsilon closure (q) = Q

Correct answer

After converting 𝜖-NFA into an NFA without epsilon moves the number of states may increase.

After converting 𝜖-NFA into an NFA without epsilon moves the number of final states will not be changed.

Solution

Hide

For any state q, the epsilon closure of q cannot be an empty set, i.e. epsilon closure (q) ≠ 𝜙. The reason is as epsilon closure (q) will contain minimum “q”, since the epsilon closure of any state is that state itself.

For any state q, the epsilon closure of q may be set of all states Q present in NFA, i.e. epsilon closure (q) = Q. For example: Q={q1,q2,q3} then it is possible that epsilon closure(q1)= {q1,q2,q3}.

After converting 𝜖-NFA into an NFA without epsilon moves the number of states always remains the same, while number of final states may increase.

Regular Expression

Select the correct option. [MSQ]

Emptiness problem is decidable for CSL.

Completeness problem is undecidable for CFL.

Correct answer

Whether a given DCFL is regular is a decidable problem.

Correct answer

Membership problem for recursively enumerable is undecidable.

Correct answer

Solution

Hide

Whether a given CSL is empty is undecidable. Whether a given CFL is ∑* (completeness problem) is undecidable for CFL. Whether a given DCFL is regular is a decidable problem. Membership problem for recursively enumerable is undecidable.

Question 19

Comparison of DFA and NFA

Consider the following FAs M1 and M2 over ∑={a,b}. Assume L(M1) and L(M2) is the language accepted by the M1 and M2 respectively. [MSQ]

Select the correct option.﻿

L(M1) is the complement of L(M2)

L(M1) ∪ L(M2) = ∑*

Correct answer

Correct answer

Solution

Hide

L(M1) =(a+b)* a(a+b)* and L(M2) =(a+b)* . Please note M2 is a NFA where initial state is final state and contains self loop of a and b, so L(M2)=(a+b)*. Complement of L(M2)=∅

Thus L(M1) is not the complement of L(M2).

Since L(M2)=∑* thus L(M1) ∪ L(M2) = ∑* and L(M1) ∩ L(M2)=L(M1).

Question 20

You didn't Attempt

Your time taken: 0s
Comparison of DFA and NFA

If L is a regular language, then which of the following is also regular. [MSQ]

L1={ x | x ∊ ∑* , y ∊ ∑* & xy ∊ L}

Correct answer

L2={ y | x ∊ ∑* , y ∊ ∑* & xy ∊ L}

Correct answer

L3={ xy | x ∊ L , y ∊ L^R where L^R is reverse of L}

Correct answer

L4={ww^R | w ∊ L and w^R is reverse of w }

Solution

Hide

L1 is prefix(L), i.e., L1 contains all strings which is prefix of some string in L.

If L is a regular language then we can make FA for L1 also. For example,

If L contains string "abcd" (assume L contains only one string)

The prefix (L) will contain strings -> { 𝜖, a, ab, abc, abcd}

Suppose for L we have a DFA M1 which contains one final state.

Then for prefix(L) we have to make all other states (except dead state) as final state.

Similarly, L2 is suffix(L), i.e., L2 contains all strings which is suffix of some string in L.

If L is a regular language then we can make FA for L2 also.


L3 is equivalent to L . L^R , since L is regular so its reversal language L^R will also regular and their concatenation is also regular.


L4 is non-regular as L={ww^R } is a well known CFL.

Question 25

You didn't Attempt

Your time taken: 0s
Operators of Regular Expression

Consider the given below languages L1 and L2.

L1= { a^n b^m c^m d^n | m,n ≥ 0}

L2= { a^n b^n c^m d^m | m,n ≥ 0 }

Select the correct statement about, L such that


L is DCFL but not regular

L is CFL but not DCFL

Correct answer

L is CSL but not CFL

L is regular

Solution

Hide

The strings in L1 are {ϵ, abcd, abbccd, aabcdd, ……..} and L1 is DCFL

The strings in L2 are {ϵ, abcd, aabbcd, abccdd, ……..} and L2 is DCFL

(L1 ∪ L2 ) = { ϵ, abcd,, abbccd, aabcdd,aabbcd, abccdd,aabbccdd,…….}. Hence (L1 ∪ L2 ) is CFL as push and pop deterministically can not be defined.

= = { ϵ, abcd, aabbccdd,………}. Hence (L1 ∩ L2 ) is CSL as it is the language { a^nb^nc^n d^n | n ≥ 0 }

(L1 ∪ L2 ) – (L1 ∩ L2 ) = { ϵ, abcd, abbccd, aabcdd,aabbcd, abccdd, aabbccdd,……..} – { ϵ, abcd, aabbccdd…….}

So L= { abbccd, aabcdd,aabbcd, abccdd,……..} which is CFL but not DCFL.

Question 26

Operators of Regular Expression

Consider the given below languages L1 and L2. Select the correct option. [MSQ]

L2= { a^n b^n c^m d^m | m,n ≥ 0 }

L1 U L2 is CFL but not DCFL.

L1 ∩ L2 is CSL but not CFL.

Solution

Hide

The strings in L1 are {ϵ, abcd,, abbccd, aabcdd, ……..} and L1 is DCFL

(L1 ∪ L2 ) = { ϵ, abcd,, abbccd, aabcdd,aabbcd, abccdd,aabbccdd,…….}. Hence (L1 ∪ L2 ) is CFL as push and pop deterministically can’t be defined.

(L1 ∩ L2 ) = { ϵ, abcd, aabbccdd,………}. Hence (L1 ∩ L2 ) is CSL as it is the language { a^n b^n c^n d^n | n ≥ 0 }

Question 29

You didn't Attempt

Your time taken: 0s
Decision Properties of CFL's

Consider the following languages.

= {a^p b^q c^r d^s | p – s = r – q for all p,q,r,s >0 }

= = { a^p b^q c^r d^s | p – r = s – q for all p,q,r,s >0}

Select the correct option:

Both L1 and L2 are CFL

Correct answer

Both L1 and L2 are not CFL

L1 is CFL while L2 is not CFL

L1 is not CFL while L2 is CFL

Solution

Hide

= = {a^p b^q c^r d^s | p – s = r – q for all p,q,r,s >0 } and = = { a^p b^q c^r d^s | p – r = s – q for all p,q,r,s >0}


Both can be rewritten as L = {a^p b^q c^r d^s | p +q = r +s for all p,q,r,s >0 } which is clearly CFL. We need to push all a’s and b’s and then for each c’s and d’s pop every symbol from the stack. If at the end both stack and input are empty then accept else rejects.

Converting Context Free Grammar to Chomsky Normal Form

Which of the following languages over ∑={a,b} are context free. [MSQ]

L1={ a^n b^n ww^r | n>0}

Correct answer

L2={ w a^n b^n w^r | n>0}

Correct answer

L3={ wa^n w^r b^n | n>0}

L4={ a^n ww^r b^n | n>0}

Correct answer

Solution

Hide

L3 is not context free. Suppose we push w and then a^n , now we have top of stack a^n . So now we cannot match w with w^r . Hence this is not CFL and rest all are CFL.

Question 32

You didn't Attempt

Your time taken: 0s
Configuration of Turing Machine

Consider the following languages.

= { <M> | M takes at least 2022 steps on input “aabb” }

= { <M> | M takes exactly 2022 steps on input “aabb” }

where for each Turing machine M, <M> denotes specific encoding of M.

Select the correct option.



is recursive and is recursively enumerable but not recursive.

is recursively enumerable and is not recursively enumerable.

Both and are recursive.

Correct answer

Both and are recursively enumerable, but not recursive.

Solution

Hide

Counting steps is always a terminating process (it means we can always check the number of steps taken by a Turing machine for some string in a finite time).

Hence both are recursive languages.


Question 33

You didn't Attempt

Your time taken: 0s
Turing Machine Construction

Consider the following languages.

= { <M,w> | M takes at most 2022 steps on some input }

= { <M> | M takes at least 2022 steps on all input }

where for each Turing machine M, <M> denotes specific encoding of M and w is a string.

Select the correct option.


is recursive and is recursively enumerable but not recursive.

is recursively enumerable and is not recursively enumerable.

Both and are recursive.

Correct answer

Both and are recursively enumerable, but not recursive.

Solution

Hide

Since counting any number of steps can be always decided. We can simulate TM (M) whether it takes at most 2022 steps on some input string which has length upto 2022. If it happens then reach to accepting (YES) state else reject (NO).


Similarly, We can simulate TM (M) whether it takes at least 2022 steps on each input string which has length upto 2022. If it happens then reach to accepting (YES) state else reject (NO).


We are taking string only length upto 2022, since if it is true for 2022 length string then definitely it will be true for string length greater than 2022.
